NOV. 8, 2010By WAYNE LUSVARDICalifornia’s often-myopic embrace of “green power” may soon come back to hurt the state.
As the Wall Street Journal aptly points out, socializing green power transmission wouldn’t be considered if it were economically viable in the first place.
This would undercut California’s plans for green power to bail out the state from its budget deficits partly caused by dependence on imported power.
23, that would have delayed the roll out of green power in California until unemployment dropped from 12 percent to 5.5 percent.
The apparent message sent by voters is that they want the green jobs promised under California’s green power Law.